# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghan-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:afghan-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to Deutsche Welle in September 2021, 250 remain in the country after 67 were evacuated to India.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] There was a small Jewish community in Afghanistan, living mainly in Herat and Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Over the years, this small community was forced to leave due to decades of warfare and religious persecution.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] By the end of the twentieth century, nearly the entire community had emigrated to Israel and the United States, with one known exception, Herat-born Zablon Simintov.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] He remained for years, being the caretaker of the only remaining Afghan synagogue.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] He left the country for the US after the second Taliban takeover.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] A woman who left shortly after him has since been identified as the likely last Jew in Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Christians, who number 500–8,000, practice their faith secretly due to intense societal opposition, and there are no public churches.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Education in Afghanistan is overseen by the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Higher Education.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] There are over 16,000 schools in the country and roughly 9 million students.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Of this, about 60% are males and 40% females.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] However, the new regime has thus far forbidden female teachers and female students from returning to secondary schools.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Over 174,000 students are enrolled in different universities around the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Former Education Minister Ghulam Farooq Wardak had stated that construction of 8,000 schools is required for the remaining children who are deprived of formal learning.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of 2018 the literacy rate of the population age 15 and older is 43.02% (males 55.48% and females 29.81%).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The top universities in Afghanistan are the American University of Afghanistan (AUAF) followed by Kabul University (KU), both of which are located in Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The National Military Academy of Afghanistan, modeled after the United States Military Academy at West Point, was a four-year military development institution dedicated to graduating officers for the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Afghan Defense University was constructed near Qargha in Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Major universities outside of Kabul include Kandahar University in the south, Herat University in the northwest, Balkh University and Kunduz University in the north, Nangarhar University and Khost University in the east.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] After the Taliban regained power in 2021, it became unclear to what extent female education would continue in the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In March 2022, after they had been closed for some time, it was announced that secondary education would be reopened shortly.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] However, shortly before reopening, the order was rescinded and schools for older girls remained closed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Despite the ban, six provinces, Balkh, Kunduz, Jowzjan, Sar-I-Pul, Faryab, and the Day Kundi, still allow girls' schools from grade 6 and up.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In December 2023, investigations were being held by the United Nations on the claim that Afghan girls of all ages were allowed to study at religious schools.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] As of November 2024, some parts of the country allow women to attend religious schools to pursue dentistry, nursing, and other subjects.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] According to the Human Development Index, Afghanistan is the 15th least developed country in the world.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The average life expectancy is estimated to be around 60 years.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country's maternal mortality rate is 396 deaths/100,000 live births and its infant mortality rate is 66 to 112.8 deaths in every 1,000 live births.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The Ministry of Public Health plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 for every 100,000 live births before 2020.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The country has more than 3,000 midwives, with an additional 300 to 400 being trained each year.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] There are over 100 hospitals in Afghanistan, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The French Medical Institute for Children and Indira Gandhi Children's Hospital in Kabul are the leading children's hospitals in the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Some of the other leading hospitals in Kabul include the Jamhuriat Hospital and Jinnah Hospital.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] In spite of all this, many Afghans travel to Pakistan and India for advanced treatment.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It was reported in 2006 that nearly 60% of the Afghan population lives within a two-hour walk of the nearest health facility.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] The disability rate is also high in Afghanistan due to the decades of war.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] It was reported recently that about 80,000 people are missing limbs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p02] Non-governmental charities such as Save the Children and Mahboba's Promise assist orphans in association with governmental structures.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have both common cultural features and those that differ between the regions of Afghanistan, each with distinctive cultures partly as a result of geographic obstacles that divide the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Family is the mainstay of Afghan society and families are often headed by a patriarch.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In the southern and eastern region, the people live according to the Pashtun culture by following Pashtunwali (the Pashtun way).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Key tenets of Pashtunwali include hospitality, the provision of sanctuary to those seeking refuge, and revenge for the shedding of blood.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Pashtuns are largely connected to the culture of Central Asia and the Iranian Plateau.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The remaining Afghans are culturally Persian and Turkic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Some non-Pashtuns who live in proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali in a process called Pashtunization, while some Pashtuns have been Persianized.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Those who have lived in Pakistan and Iran over the last 30 years have been further influenced by the cultures of those neighboring nations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan people are known to be strongly religious.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghans, particularly Pashtuns, are noted for their tribal solidarity and high regard for personal honor.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] There are various Afghan tribes, and an estimated 2–3 million nomads.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghan culture is deeply Islamic, but pre-Islamic practices persist.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Child marriage is prevalent; in 2017, Human Rights Watch described the legal age for marriage of girls as being 16, or 15 with the consent of the father or a judge.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The most preferred marriage in Afghan society is to one's parallel cousin, and the groom is often expected to pay a bride price.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In the villages, families typically occupy mudbrick houses, or compounds with mudbrick or stone walled houses.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Villages typically have a headman (*malik*), a master for water distribution (*mirab*) and a religious teacher (*mullah*).
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Men would typically work on the fields, joined by women during harvest.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] About 15% of the population are nomadic, locally called *kochis*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] When nomads pass villages they often buy supplies such as tea, wheat and kerosene from the villagers; villagers buy wool and milk from the nomads.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghan clothing for both men and women typically consists of various forms of shalwar kameez, especially *perahan tunban* and *khet partug*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Women would normally wear a *chador* for head covering; some women, typically from highly conservative communities, wear the *burqa*, a full body covering.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] These were worn by some women of the Pashtun community well before Islam came to the region, but the Taliban enforced this dress on women when they were in power.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Another popular dress is the *chapan* which acts as a coat.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The *karakul* is a hat made from the fur of a specific regional breed of sheep.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] It was favored by former kings of Afghanistan and became known to much of the world in the 21st century when it was constantly worn by President Hamid Karzai.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The *pakol* is another traditional hat originating from the far east of the country; it was popularly worn by the guerrilla leader Ahmad Shah Massoud.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The *Mazari hat* originates from northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan contains many remnants from all ages, including Greek and Buddhist stupas, monasteries, monuments, temples, and Islamic minarets.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Among the most well known are the Great Mosque of Herat, the Blue Mosque, the Minaret of Jam, the Chil Zena, the Qala-i Bost in Lashkargah, the ancient Greek city of Ai-Khanoum.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in modern times due to the civil wars.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The two famous Buddhas of Bamiyan were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as idolatrous.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] As there was no colonialism in the modern era in Afghanistan, European-style architecture is rare but does exist: the Victory Arch at Paghman and the Darul Aman Palace in Kabul were built in this style in the 1920s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghan architecture also ranges deep into India such as the city of Agra, and the tomb of Sher Shah Suri, an Afghan Emperor of India.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Carpet weaving is an ancient practice in Afghanistan, and many of these are still handmade by tribal and nomadic people today.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Carpets have been produced in the region for thousands of years and traditionally done by women.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Some crafters express their feelings through the designs of rugs; for example after the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, "war rugs", a variant of Afghan rugs, were created with designs representing pain and misery caused by the conflict.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Every province has its own specific characteristics in making rugs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In some of the Turkic-populated areas in the north-west, bride and wedding ceremony prices are driven by the bride's weaving skills.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Pottery has been crafted in Afghanistan for millennia.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The village of Istalif, north of Kabul, is in particular a major center, known for its unique turquoise and green pottery, and their methods of crafting have remained the same for centuries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Much of *lapis lazuli* stones were earthed in modern-day Afghanistan which were used in Chinese porcelain as cobalt blue, later used in ancient Mesopotamia and Turkey.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The lands of Afghanistan have a long history of art, with the world's earliest known usage of oil painting found in cave murals in the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] A notable art style that developed in Afghanistan and eastern Pakistan is Gandhara Art, produced by a fusion of Greco-Roman art and Buddhist art between the 1st and 7th centuries CE.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Later eras saw increased use of the Persian miniature style, with Kamaleddin Behzad of Herat being one of the most notable miniature artists of the Timurid and early Safavid periods.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Since the 1900s, the nation began to use Western techniques in art.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Abdul Ghafoor Breshna was a prominent Afghan painter and sketch artist from Kabul during the 20th century.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Classic Persian and Pashto poetry are a cherished part of Afghan culture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Poetry has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] One of the poetic styles is called landay.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] A popular theme in Afghan folklore and mythology are Divs, monstrous creatures.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Thursdays are traditionally "poetry night" in the city of Herat when men, women and children gather and recite both ancient and modern poems.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Pashto literature, although quantitatively remarkable and in great growth in the last century, has always had an essentially local meaning and importance, feeling the influence of both Persian literature and the contiguous literatures of India.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Both main literatures, from the second half of the nineteenth century, have shown themselves to be sensitive to genres, movements and stylistic features imported from Europe.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Khushal Khan Khattak of the 17th century is considered the national poet.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Other notable poets include Rabi'a Balkhi, Jami, Rahman Baba, Khalilullah Khalili, and Parween Pazhwak.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghan classical music has close historical links with Indian classical music and use the same Hindustani terminology and theories like raga.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Genres of this style of music include ghazal (poetic music) and instruments such as the Indian tabla, sitar and harmonium, and local instruments like zerbaghali, as well as dayereh and tanbur which are also known in Central Asia, the Caucasus and the Middle East.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The rubab is the country's national instrument and precurses the Indian sarod instrument.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Some of the famous artists of classical music include Ustad Sarahang and Sarban.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Pop music developed in the 1950s through Radio Kabul and was influential in social change.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] During this time female artists also started appearing, at first Mermon Parwin.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Perhaps the most famous artist of this genre was Ahmad Zahir, who synthesized many genres and continues to be renowned for his voice and rich lyrics long after his death in 1979.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Other notable masters of traditional or popular Afghan music include Nashenas, Ubaidullah Jan, Mahwash, Ahmad Wali, Farhad Darya, and Naghma.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Attan is the national dance of Afghanistan, a group dance popularly performed by Afghans of all backgrounds.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The dance is considered part of Afghan identity.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan has around 350 radio stations and over 200 television stations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Radio Television Afghanistan, originating from 1925, is the state public broadcaster.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Television programs began airing in the 1970s and today there are many private television channels such as TOLO and Shamshad TV.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The first Afghan newspaper was published in 1873, and there are hundreds of print outlets today.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] By the 1920s, Radio Kabul was broadcasting local radio services.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Voice of America, BBC, and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL) broadcast in both of Afghanistan's official languages on radio.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Press restrictions have been gradually relaxed and private media diversified since 2002, after more than two decades of tight controls.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have long been accustomed to watching Indian Bollywood films and listening to its filmi songs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] It has been claimed that Afghanistan is among the biggest markets for the Hindi film industry.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The stereotypes of Afghans in India (*Kabuliwala* or *Pathani*) have also been represented in some Bollywood films by actors.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Many Bollywood film stars have roots in Afghanistan, including Salman Khan, Saif Ali Khan, Aamir Khan, Feroz Khan, Kader Khan, Naseeruddin Shah, Zarine Khan, Celina Jaitly, and a number of others.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Several Bollywood films have been shot inside Afghanistan, including *Dharmatma*, *Khuda Gawah*, *Escape from Taliban*, and *Kabul Express*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghan cuisine is largely based upon the nation's chief crops, such as wheat, maize, barley and rice.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Accompanying these staples are native fruits and vegetables as well as dairy products such as milk, yogurt, and whey.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Kabuli palaw is the national dish of Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The nation's culinary specialties reflect its ethnic and geographic diversity.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan is known for its high-quality pomegranates, grapes, and sweet melons.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] A typical Afghan diet consists of naan, yogurt, rice, and meat.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan's official New Year starts with Nowruz (natively known as "*Nawroz*"), an ancient tradition that started as a Zoroastrian celebration in present-day Iran, and with which it shares the annual celebration along with several other countries.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] It occurs every year at the vernal equinox.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In Afghanistan, Nowruz is typically celebrated with music and dance, as well as holding buzkashi tournaments.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Yaldā, another nationally celebrated ancient tradition, commemorates the ancient goddess Mithra and marks the longest night of the year on the eve of the winter solstice (*Čilli-yi Zimistān*; usually falling on 20 or 21 December), during which families gather together to recite poetry and eat fruit.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] As a predominantly Muslim country, Islamic events and festivals such as Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr and Ashura are widely celebrated annually in Afghanistan.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Sikh festival of Vaisakhi is celebrated by the Sikh community and the Hindu festival Diwali by the Hindu community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] National Independence Day is celebrated on 19 August to mark the Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919 and the country's full independence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Several international celebrations are also officially held in Afghanistan, such as International Workers' Day, and International Women's Day.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Some regional festivals include the Red Flower Festival (during Nowruz) in Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Damboora Festival in Bamyan Province.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Sport in Afghanistan is managed by the Afghan Sports Federation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Cricket and association football are the two most popular sports in the country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Sports Federation promotes cricket, association football, basketball, volleyball, golf, handball, boxing, taekwondo, weightlifting, bodybuilding, track and field, skating, bowling, snooker, chess, and other sports.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national basketball team won the first team sports title at the 2010 South Asian Games.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In 2012, the country's 3x3 basketball team won the gold medal at the 2012 Asian Beach Games.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] In 2013, Afghanistan's football team followed as it won the SAFF Championship.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan national cricket team, which was formed in 2001, won the 2009–10 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The team played in the 2015, 2019, and 2023 Cricket World Cups.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) is the official governing body of the sport and is based in Kabul.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground serves as the nation's main cricket stadium.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] There are several other stadiums throughout the country, including the Ghazi Amanullah Khan International Cricket Stadium near Jalalabad.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] Domestically, cricket is played between teams from different provinces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national football team has been competing in international football since 1941.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The national team plays its home games at the Ghazi Stadium in Kabul, while football in Afghanistan is governed by the Afghanistan Football Federation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The national team has never competed or qualified for the FIFA World Cup but won an international football trophy in 2013.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The country also has a national team in the sport of futsal, a 5-a-side variation of football.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The traditional and the national sport of Afghanistan is buzkashi, particularly popular in the north.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] It is similar to polo, played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass.
[src:afghan-sign-language/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Hound (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan and was used in wolf hunting.
[src:afghan-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Akitiri is often used when speech is impractical or not preferred and this includes when people are communicating across long distances, hunting, when wishing to speak privately and during ceremony and times of mourning.
[src:afghan-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] Hand signs are also frequently used alongside speech and is more commonly used by women of the community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] In many Kaytetye communities fluency in Akitiri is highly valued but, due to the impacts of colonisation, use is declining and younger generations often use it in a different or simplified way.
[src:afghan-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] A 2023 project to revitalise the Kaytetye language and Akitiri sign language was the Kaytetyemoji app which created 122 emojis including 44 specific to life on Kaytetye country.
[src:afghan-sign-language/akitiri-sign-language] These emoji's often directly reflect the hand signs of Akitiri and, as part of the development of the app, many younger generations were taught new signs to them.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] As deafness is so frequent (4% of the village's population is deaf, compared to 0.1% in the United States) and deaf and hearing people share a language, deaf people are not stigmatised in this community and marriage between deaf and hearing people is common.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL grammar developed quickly, with the signing of each generation becoming more complex than the last.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Even though no evidence of phonological structure was found throughout the community, it seems to be emerging within individual families.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] In 2004, the Al-Sayyid community numbered around 3,000, most of whom trace their ancestry to the time the village was founded, in the mid-19th century, by a local woman and an Egyptian man.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Two of this founding couple's five sons carried a gene for nonsyndromic, genetically recessive, profound pre-lingual neurosensory deafness.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The descendants of the founding couple often married their cousins owing to the tribe's rejection by its neighbours for being "foreign fellahin".
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The gene became homozygous in several members of the family.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Four deaf siblings were born into the community approximately 75 years after its founding.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Deafness spread to other families in the following two generations; in 2011 there were about 120–150 deaf individuals in the community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This unique set of circumstances led to a sociolinguistic environment not often found elsewhere.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The deaf individuals were not only accepted into the greater community, but the resulting sign language was being used by a significant proportion of hearing people in the community as well.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Additionally, Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language is being passed down from generation to generation in a natural social setting.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] There is no separate deaf culture or politics.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL was first studied in the late 1990s by anthropologist Shifra Kisch and came to worldwide attention in February 2005 when an international group of researchers published a study of the language in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The spontaneous emergence of the language in the last 70 years and the development of a complex grammar in near-isolation are of particular interest to linguists for the insights it provides into the birth of human language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The community was isolated from the outside not by geography, but by social stigma.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Contact with the outside world is growing as pupils are exposed to Israeli Sign Language and Jordanian Sign Language in schools and community members are marrying outside the community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Scholars study ABSL because, as deaf people in Al-Sayyid cannot hear Arabic or Hebrew and they have not been exposed to any other sign languages, ABSL is a brand new language, uninfluenced by any other.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL is in its early stages, so researchers are observing the language as it develops.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL consistently shows subject–object–verb (SOV) word order (e.g., "woman child feed") and head-modifier order.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] SVO order is prominent only when the object is a pronoun.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This word order is marked contrast to the dialect of Arabic spoken by hearing members of the community (SVO) as well as Hebrew (SVO), classical Arabic (VSO) and the predominant sign languages in the region, Israeli Sign Language and Jordanian Sign Language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL has a tendency to limit predicates to containing one animate argument.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Events involving multiple animate referents are therefore often conveyed through the use of multiple clauses as seen below.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL is seen as evidence for the human tendency to construct communication along grammatical lines.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Researchers have remarked on the speed with which a grammar emerged, with the SOV word-order emerging with the first generation of signers, as well as the continuing rapid development of the language: the third generation is signing twice as fast as the first and is using longer sentences.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL does not contain "agreeing" verbs as most known sign languages do.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Few syntactic markers such as complementizers, signs to signal conditionals or structures to mark questions have been found.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] These functions are instead expressed through the use of prosodic cues to designate when a clause starts or ends or in order to link them together.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, conditional and when-clauses are marked by raising the eyebrows and tilting the head forward.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL has not been found to have a fully fledged phonology.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This can be seen in the absence of duality of patterning, which means signs in ABSL cannot be analyzed as being composed of smaller, meaningless units.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Other features common of phonologies, such as signs differing in single feature or rigid constraints on well-formed signs were also not found.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Sign features that often contrast in established sign languages, such as where the sign is articulated or the orientation of the hand do not seem relevant.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Mouthing, the visual depictions of spoken words with the mouth, is not used.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] It seemed that the ABSL speakers were "aiming for an iconic and holistic prototype" when producing a sign rather than adhering to strictly defined features, which is what one would expect from a language with a phonology.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The form of a given sign varies considerably throughout the community and is understood by others through iconicity.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] However, within households that have fluent deaf or hearing signers the signs have a much more conventionalized agreed-upon form.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Certain phonological processes, such as assimilation of handshape within a compound, have also been observed within families.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] These types of households might eventually give rise to the type of phonology found in more established sign languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] New signs are often creating through compounding, whereby two noun signs are combined.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] One method of compounding includes the addition of what appears to be an affix to the base sign to indicate its length.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This length affix cannot be used in isolation and is produced by touching the wrist with the non-dominant hand at different points to indicate the relative length of the object in question.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The dominant hand meanwhile indicates its thickness through the extension of more or less fingers.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, the word 'pencil' is translated with the compound 'WRITE+LONG-THIN-OBJECT' by first performing the sign for WRITE, then extending the index finger to represent the pencil and having the other hand represent its relative length.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This compound also undergoes handshape assimilation, whereby both hands take on the same handshape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This could be considered as the beginnings of a phonology.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Some signs have been found to not iconically represent the concept in question.
[src:afghan-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, the sign for "man" is formed by the curling of the finger in the shape of a moustache although Bedouin men no longer wear them.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:afghan-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:afghan-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
